rificing professional authority and power.Bridging institutional and cultural history, the book brings together a variety of elements of socialism as enacted by planners on a competitive urban stage, such as scientific debate, the crafting of symbolic landscapes, and state campaigns for the development of cultured cities and people. By examining how planners and other urban inhabitants experienced, lived, and struggled with socialism and Stalinism, DeHaan offers readers a much broader, more complex picture of planning and planners than has been revealed to date.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aArchitecturexPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxSoviet UnionxElectronic books. 0aArchitecturexPolitical aspectszSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 0aCity plannersxHistoryx20th centuryxSoviet Union. 0aCity plannerszSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 0aCity planningxHistoryx20th centuryxSoviet Union. 0aCity planningxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxSoviet Union. 0aCity planningxPolitical aspectszSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 0aCity planningzSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266240740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442662407423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442662407.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK